============================================================
THEOREM: Non-dominant eigenvalue contribution
============================================================
lambda_1(x) ~ 1 + 2x: contributes to ALL m values
lambda_{2,3}(x) ~ +/- i*sqrt(x): contribute ONLY at m=2 (N even)

Consequence: g_k(m) for m >= 3 is determined SOLELY by lambda_1.
The dominant eigenvalue gives [x^k] lambda_1^N = degree-k polynomial in N.
g_k(m) for m >= 3 is a degree-k polynomial in m.

At m=1: g_k(1) = 1 for all k (boundary condition).
At m=2: g_k(2) = 2k (includes lambda_{2,3} correction).

The opus degree-3 fit absorbs the m=2 correction into the polynomial,
but this forces the polynomial to have the WRONG degree for m >= 5.
Both give the same CV^2 sum because the errors redistribute across k-levels.

